                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City Policeman</hi> 428). I was Called on the morning of 17th April to take the prisoner—he said he was taking the pin to the door to look at it, and that he had 1, 250<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in his pocket—I searched him at the station and found 9<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on him with cards and papers, including these cards of jewellers, (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>): Sir John Bennett, Cheapside, and Burlton, jeweller, 59, Cheapside, and a receipt which he explained to me as being, a receipt for 15, 000 florins in the Four per Cent Dutch Consols; 12, 000 in the name of Horton, and 3, 000 in the' name of Dr. Part, but it has been explained to me by the Consul that they had been mortgaged and were quite useless to the prisoner.</p>
